## Phase 0 — Reality check (MANDATORY before drafting slices)

Most bad design plans propose `build` slices for things that are already (partially) shipped. You **must** ground the plan in what already exists before writing the slice list. Do not skip this step.

For each capability the phase intends to deliver, gather evidence in **two** layers and record it in the `## Existing Implementation` section of the plan (see required structure below).

### Layer A — Codebase inventory (always required)

Use [`grep_search`](../../README.md) (and `read_file` on the matches) — not memory — to inventory existing code that touches the phase's surface. For each capability, capture either:

- One or more `path/to/file.ts:LINE` references showing the shipped behavior, **or**
- An explicit "no existing code found for `<capability>` (searched: `<patterns>`)" line. Negative evidence is still evidence; an unchecked capability is not.

If you discover code that already partially implements a slice, you must say so explicitly and reframe the slice to `wire-up`, `augment`, `audit`, or `drop` (see Slice Kind below) — never silently propose `build` over existing code.

### Layer B — Deployed/runnable surface (when applicable)

If the project has a running surface and you have access to inspect it (browser tools, a local dev server you can curl, a deployed URL), **inspect it before drafting slices**. The whole point of a design plan is to be grounded in observable reality, not speculation.

- **Web/UI projects**: navigate the relevant pages with browser tools (or have the autonomous-builder do so via Explore). Note which UI elements, sections, CTAs, placeholder states, etc. are already rendered. Capture screenshots or DOM excerpts when material.
- **API/CLI projects**: probe the relevant endpoints/commands. Record the actual response shape and observed behavior.
- **No deployed/runnable surface available**: write `Layer B: n/a — <one-line reason>` (e.g., "pre-deploy phase, no runnable surface yet"). Do not fabricate.

If you do not have the tools to inspect Layer B yourself but the project clearly has a runnable surface, **return to the autonomous-builder with the inspection request** — the builder dispatches the catalog `designer` agent (browser walkthroughs) or runs API/CLI probes itself, then re-dispatches you with the findings appended to the plan. Do not write `Layer B: n/a` because you personally lack browser tools; that is the failure mode this step exists to prevent. If `designer` is not activated under `.github/agents/`, the builder must surface `/catalog-review activate designer` to the human first.

The [evidence-gathering skill](../../skills/evidence-gathering/SKILL.md) covers the audit patterns (curl/jq, schema dumps, file inventory).

## Task

Write `roadmap/phases/phase-N-design.md` (where `N` = next phase from CURRENT-STATE). The file **must** contain every section below, in this order.

### Required structure

```markdown
# Phase N: <Title>

## Status
draft | in-critique | approved | waived

## Goal
One paragraph: what this phase delivers and why.

## Existing Implementation (Reality Check)
_Required. Output of Phase 0 above. Do not skip; the critic will treat a missing or hand-waved Reality Check as a Blocking finding._

**Layer A — Codebase inventory**
- **`<capability 1>`**: <file:line evidence | "no existing code found (searched: `<patterns>`)">
- **`<capability 2>`**: ...

**Layer B — Deployed/runnable surface**
- **`<surface 1>`**: <observation, with screenshot/excerpt where material | "n/a — <reason>">
- **`<surface 2>`**: ...

**Implications for slices**: short paragraph mapping what's already shipped to which slices below are `build` vs `wire-up` vs `augment` vs `audit` vs `drop`.

## User Stories
_(populated by product-owner handoff; leave as `(to be populated by product-owner)` if not yet invoked)_

- **As a** <user> **I want to** <capability> **so that** <outcome>.

## Acceptance Criteria
Measurable outcomes per story.
- [ ] Criterion 1 (observable, verifiable)
- [ ] Criterion 2

## Non-Goals
Explicit exclusions to prevent scope creep.
- Not doing X because Y.

## Risks
- **Risk**: description — **Mitigation**: approach.

## ADR Candidates
Decisions in this phase that warrant capture in `docs/architecture/decisions/`.
- ADR-NNN (proposed): <decision title> — captures choice between A vs B.

## Test Strategy
Map each acceptance criterion to a test layer.
- Unit: ...
- Integration: ...
- End-to-end: ...
- Manual: ...

## Slice Breakdown
Ordered, independently-shippable slices with file-level hints. Each slice **must** declare a `Kind` and reference the Existing Implementation finding(s) it relies on.

`Kind` vocabulary:
- **build** — net-new code/UI; Layer A + B confirmed nothing exists.
- **wire-up** — DOM/scaffolding/data exists but is unwired or stubbed (e.g. "Coming soon" placeholder); slice connects it.
- **augment** — feature partially shipped; slice extends it (e.g. add per-row link to existing list).
- **audit** — feature appears shipped; slice verifies consistency/accessibility/edge cases without new build.
- **drop** — slice was originally proposed but Reality Check revealed it is already shipped; record why so the next round doesn't re-add it.

1. **Slice 1 — <name>** (Kind: <build|wire-up|augment|audit|drop>): files touched, scope, tests to write. Grounded in Existing Implementation: <bullet ref or "no prior code">.
2. **Slice 2 — <name>** (Kind: ...): ...
```

## After writing

Direct edits to `roadmap/state.md` are blocked by `tool-guardrails.py`. Stamp the planning fields via the sanctioned helper:

```bash
python3 .github/hooks/scripts/write-plan-evidence.py design-plan roadmap/phases/phase-N-design.md
python3 .github/hooks/scripts/write-plan-evidence.py design-status draft
```

The helper validates that the plan file exists and that the status value is in the canonical vocabulary (`draft | in-critique | approved | revise | rethink | waived`).

## Handoff

When the draft is complete, hand off to:

- **product-owner** — to populate the User Stories section.
- **critic** — for adversarial review (only after product-owner if applicable).

> **If you are the planner subagent dispatched by `autonomous-builder`, skip this section.** Nested subagent invocation is disabled by default (`chat.subagents.allowInvocationsFromSubagents`), and the builder owns the `planning → design-critique` transition explicitly. The builder will dispatch product-owner and critic itself once it sees `Design Status: draft`. Act on the Handoff section only when a human invoked you directly via `/design-plan`.

## Rules

- **Reality first.** Phase 0 is mandatory — slice authoring without a populated `## Existing Implementation` section is a Blocking critic finding, not a stylistic preference. Half-shipped functionality is the most common (and most expensive) design failure mode.
- Do **not** make implementation decisions here — that's `/implementation-plan`.
- Flag unresolved blockers in `docs/reference/open-questions.md`; do not paper over them.
- Do not edit source code. Your scope is plan files + `state.md`.
- Respect authority order: VISION-LOCK > ADRs > architecture > roadmap. If this phase would contradict a higher doc, raise it instead of silently working around it.
